  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 桂陽守孫得之讓起復不允批答
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 云云。夫人子之欲終喪制。固其情也禮也。宜若不可奪之。然仲尼所以制墨縗從事者。蓋亦順變適宜而非必薄於親者也。汝早擢龍頭。榮參鷺序。忠義之誠貫乎日。遠不忘君。孝敬之性資諸天。勤於事母。頃從西掖。出守南州。方興有袴之歌。遽致枕苫之患。坐移流景。已踰百日之期。宜假吉儀。往徇一方之愛。夫何泥古而守志。不欲割哀而從權。况桂陽殘邑也。頻遭歲儉。民有菜色。非若爾之廉平。孰能撫吾疲民哉。雖以情陳。固難頷肯云云。
korean:
  title: 계양수 손득지 양 기복 불윤 비답
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 운운. 대개 아들로서 부모의 상제(喪制)를 마치려 함은 진실로 정(情)이요 예(禮)이니, 그 뜻을 억지로 빼앗음이 불가할 듯하다. 그러나 중니(仲尼)가 검은 상복으로 국사를 보는 제도를 만든 것은, 대개 비상한 경우에 때에 따라 적당히 하게 하라는 것이요, 반드시 어버이에게 박정하게 하는 것이 아니다.그대는 일찍 과거에 장원하고 영광스럽게 조정의 반열에 참예하여, 해를 꿸 만한 충의의 정성은 멀리 임금을 잊지 않고, 하늘에서 받은 효도의 천성은 어머니를 섬김에 부지런했다. 전번에 서액(西掖)으로부터 나아가 남주(南州)의 수령이 되어 바야흐로 선정의 노래를 일으키려 하던 차에 갑자기 거적을 베는 친상(親喪)을 만났다. 관직을 떠난 지 벌써 백 일의 기한이 넘었으니, 임시로 상복을 벗고 가서 한 고을의 백성을 보는 것이 마땅하다. 그런데 어찌 예법에 구애되어 고집을 피워 애통함을 억제하여 권도(權道)를 좇지 않으려 하는가.하물며 계양(桂陽)은 쇠잔한 고을인데 여러 해째 흉년을 만나 백성들이 모두 기근에 빠진 데이겠는가. 너의 청렴하고 공평한 정사가 아니면 누가 능히 나의 곤한 백성들을 어루만져 주겠는가. 비록 진정(陳情)이 있었으나 허락할 수 없노라. 운운.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0320_020_0360&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Royal Rescript Denying the Request of Sun Duk-ji, Guardian of Gyeyang, to Extend His Mourning Leave
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    ... In truth, for a son to complete the full period of mourning for his parents accords with both filial feeling and propriety, and it seems such intention should not be denied. Yet when Confucius established the practice of conducting state affairs while wearing the dark mourning robe, it was to accommodate extraordinary circumstances with timely flexibility—not to show disrespect toward one's parents.

    You rose early through the examination to prominence and took your rightful place among the court officials. Your loyalty and sincerity shine brilliantly, never forgetting your sovereign from afar. The filial nature heaven granted you labors ceaselessly in service to your mother. Recently, departing from the Palace Library, you became magistrate of the southern province, just beginning to cultivate the songs of good governance, when suddenly you were struck by the sorrow of losing your parent. Now more than a hundred days have passed since you left your post. It is fitting that you temporarily set aside the deepest mourning and return to attend to the needs of your people.

    Why cling so rigidly to ancient custom and refuse to bend? Why resist adapting principle to circumstance, when Gyeyang itself is an impoverished district, long afflicted by poor harvests, its people gaunt from hunger? Without your honesty and fairness, who else could comfort my suffering people? Though I understand your heartfelt plea, I cannot grant it. ...
  footnotes:
    - Confucius' practice of conducting state business while in mourning (wearing the dark mourning robe) established a precedent in Chinese political philosophy for balancing filial duty with administrative responsibility.
    - The 'hundred days' refers to the period after the initial mourning when the deceased is buried, a key threshold in traditional mourning practices.
    - '''Songs of good governance'' alludes to the traditional belief that virtuous rule produces music and harmony among the people.'
    - This rescript is a royal denial of a subordinate official's request to extend his mourning leave, arguing that duty to the state and its suffering people takes precedence.
